snippet.textDisplay:
In the initial parts of a disease, as we are now for this pandemic, there is a systematic under reporting of deaths, as the overnight increase in infections have not generated their associated deaths.

If the disease were completed for the 4,515, which it is not, the 132 deaths should be attributed perhaps to yesterday’s 4,515, infected people not today’s 5,874 infected people. If this were true, which it is not quite accurate, the death rate will be 2.9%. This is about 30% larger than the rate not taking this time lag in reported deaths, due to the disease not being fully progressed.

As the total number of infected people becomes much larger than the number of current patients, thus effective or correction will become much less important. God forbid, but if the eventual rate were to increase towards this 2.9% rate, one should have comfort that the virus isn’t becoming more lethal, it is just the numbers catching up to more accurately reflect the underlying lethality all along.

snippet.textDisplay:
Here’s some math that ruined my day yesterday — —

2018-2019 US flu season; 49 million sick
Common flu has a mortality rate of 0.03%
Common flu has a contagion rate average 1:1.2

nCoV mortality rate of 3-15% (see Lancet Journal of Medicine article Jan.24)
nCoV contagion rate, 1:2.6

This thing is twice as contagious as the common flu, and 10-500 times as deadly. That means if it only spreads like last year’s flu:

49 million x 3% = 1.47 million dead
49 million x 15% = 7.35 million dead

Spanish Flu infected 1/3 of the world, and its contagion rate was lower than 1:2.6. So:

(7 billion x 0.33) x 3% = 69.3 million dead worldwide
(7 billion x 0.33) x 15% = 346.5 million dead

All in all, I think we’ll be lucky if less than 50 million worldwide die from this.
